contents.rsbHtml:
Quaternion multiplication

Multiplying two unit quaternions represents a composition of two rotations.
contents.rsbText:
'## Quaternion multiplication
Multiplying two unit quaternions represents a *composition of two rotations*.

contents.rsbHtml: Quaternion multiplication isn't commutative . If we want to apply a rotation (q_{1}) then a rotation (q_{2}), the resulting rotation (q_{3}) is: $$q_{3}=q_{2}.q_{1}$$
contents.rsbText:
'Quaternion multiplication isn't commutative . If we want to apply a rotation \(q_{1}\) then a rotation \(q_{2}\), the resulting rotation \(q_{3}\) is:
$$q_{3}=q_{2}.q_{1}$$

contents.rsbHtml: Quaternion multiplication looks like this: $$q_{1} = a+b\textrm{i}+c\textrm{j}+d\textrm{k}$$ $$q_{2} = e+f\textrm{i}+g\textrm{j}+h\textrm{k}$$
contents.rsbText:
'Quaternion multiplication looks like this:
$$q_{1} = a+b\textrm{i}+c\textrm{j}+d\textrm{k}$$
$$q_{2} = e+f\textrm{i}+g\textrm{j}+h\textrm{k}$$

contents.rsbHtml: $$ q_{1}.q_{2} = (ae-bf-cg-dh)+(af+be+ch-dg)\textrm{i}+(ag-bh+ce+df)\textrm{j}+(ah+bg-cf+de)\textrm{k} $$

instance Mul(Quaternion) def (*)(q, q') = (x , y , z , w ) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w ) (x', y', z', w') = (q'.x, q'.y, q'.z, q'.w) Quaternion( w*x' + x*w' + y*z' - z*y', w*y' - x*z' + y*w' + z*x', w*z' + x*y' - y*x' + z*w', w*w' - x*x' - y*y' - z*z' ) one = ident
contents.rsbText:
instance Mul(Quaternion)
  def (*)(q, q') =
    (x , y , z , w ) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w )
    (x', y', z', w') = (q'.x, q'.y, q'.z, q'.w)
    Quaternion( w*x' + x*w' + y*z' - z*y',
                    w*y' - x*z' + y*w' + z*x',
                    w*z' + x*y' - y*x' + z*w',
                    w*w' - x*x' - y*y' - z*z' )
  one = ident

contents.rsbHtml: Quaternion vs Euler angles

We use quaternions instead of Euler angles to represent rotations for a couple of reasons:

  • Euler angles suffer from gimbal lock
  • Interpolating between two Euler angles lead to weird results
contents.rsbText:
'We use quaternions instead of Euler angles to represent rotations for a couple of reasons:
  * Euler angles suffer from gimbal lock
  * Interpolating between two Euler angles lead to weird results

contents.rsbHtml: We represent the orientation of an object using only a quaternion, then we multiply that orientation by another quaternion to rotate it.
contents.rsbText: 'We represent the orientation of an object using only a quaternion, then we multiply that orientation by another quaternion to rotate it.

contents.rsbHtml: However writing a rotation directly in quaternion form isn't really intuitive, what we do instead is *convert an Euler angle to a quaternion then use it for rotating.
contents.rsbText: 'However writing a rotation directly in quaternion form isn't really intuitive, what we do instead is *convert an Euler angle to a quaternion then use it for rotating.

contents.rsbHtml: If we have an Euler angle rotation in the order ZYX (Yaw -> Pitch -> Roll, we can chose any order but must stay consistent), we can convert it to a quaternion like this:
contents.rsbText: 'If we have an Euler angle rotation in the order ZYX (Yaw -> Pitch -> Roll, we can chose any order but must stay consistent), we can convert it to a quaternion like this:

contents.rsbHtml: $$ q = \begin{bmatrix} \sin(x/2)\cos(y/2)\cos(z/2)-\cos(x/2)\sin(y/2)\sin(z/2) \\ \cos(x/2)\sin(y/2)\cos(z/2)+\sin(x/2)\cos(y/2)\sin(z/2) \\ \cos(x/2)\cos(y/2)\sin(z/2)-\sin(x/2)\sin(y/2)\cos(z/2) \\ \cos(x/2)\cos(y/2)\cos(z/2)+\sin(x/2)\sin(y/2)\sin(z/2) \\ \end{bmatrix} $$
data Euler = E(Fin 3=>Float)

contents.rsbHtml: Drawing with Quaternions
Libraries like three.js allow us to use quaternions directly for rotations.
contents.rsbText: 'Libraries like three.js allow us to use quaternions directly for rotations.

contents.rsbHtml: This script implements a simple 3D box positioned based on a quaternion.
contents.rsbText: 'This script implements a simple 3D box positioned based on a quaternion.

contents.rsbHtml: def show3D(q: Quaternion) -> String = (x, y, z, w) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w ) "<iframe width=\"100%\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" onload=\"this.style.height=this.contentWindow.document.body.scrollHeight+'px'\"; srcdoc='<html> <head><script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three-js@79.0.0/three.js\"></script> </head> <body> <script>const scene = new THREE.Scene(); // Generic scene construction const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera( 75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000 ); camera.position.z = 2; const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer(); renderer.setSize( window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight ); document.body.appendChild( renderer.domElement ); // Create a pretty box with lights. const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1.0, 1.0, 1.0); red = new THREE.Color(1, 0, 0); green = new THREE.Color(0, 1, 0); blue = new THREE.Color(0, 0, 1); var colors = [red, green, blue]; for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) { geometry.faces[4 * i].color = colors[i]; geometry.faces[4 * i + 1].color = colors[i]; geometry.faces[4 * i + 2].color = colors[i]; geometry.faces[4 * i + 3].color = colors[i]; } var material = new THREE.MeshBasicMaterial( { color: 0xffffff, vertexColors: true } ); // Add the cube to the scene const cube = new THREE.Mesh( geometry, material ); scene.add( cube ); // Rotate by our angles. cube.quaternion.copy(new THREE.Quaternion("<> (show x) <> ", " <> (show y) <> ", " <> (show z) <> ", " <> (show w) <> ")); renderer.render( scene, camera ); </script> </body> </html>'> </iframe>"

contents.rsbHtml: Quaternion Exp and Log
The exponential and the logarithm of a quaternion won't be very useful by themselves, but we will use them to compute other functions later.
contents.rsbText: 'The exponential and the logarithm of a quaternion won't be very useful by themselves, but we will use them to compute other functions later.

contents.rsbHtml: Given a quaternion (q = (x,y,z,w)) and its vector part (v = (x,y,z)), the exponential of that quaternion is also a quaternion, and it's given by this formula:
contents.rsbText: 'Given a quaternion \(q = (x,y,z,w)\) and its vector part \(v = (x,y,z)\), the exponential of that quaternion is also a quaternion, and it's given by this formula:

contents.rsbHtml: $$\exp(q) = \exp(w)\begin{pmatrix} \frac{v_{x}}{||v||}\sin(||v||)\\ \frac{v_{y}}{||v||}\sin(||v||)\\ \frac{v_{z}}{||v||}\sin(||v||)\\ \cos(||v||) \end{pmatrix}$$

def q_exp(q:Quaternion) -> Quaternion = (x, y, z, w) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w ) v = [x, y, z] m = magnitude v [x', y', z'] = normalize v sin_v = sin m exp_w = exp w Quaternion( x' * sin_v * exp_w, y' * sin_v * exp_w, z' * sin_v * exp_w, cos(m) * exp_w)
contents.rsbText:
def q_exp(q:Quaternion) -> Quaternion =
  (x, y, z, w) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w )
  v = [x, y, z]
  m = magnitude v
  [x', y', z'] = normalize v
  sin_v = sin m
  exp_w = exp w
  Quaternion(
    x' * sin_v * exp_w,
    y' * sin_v * exp_w,
    z' * sin_v * exp_w,
    cos(m) * exp_w)

def acos(x:Float) -> Float = negate = select (x < 0.0) 1.0 0.0 x = abs x ret1 = (-0.0187293 * x) + 0.0742610 ret2 = (ret1 * x) - 0.2121144 ret3 = (ret2 * x) + pi / 2. ret4 = (ret3 * (sqrt (1.0-x))) ret5 = ret4 - (2.0 * negate * ret4) negate * pi + ret5
contents.rsbText:
def acos(x:Float) -> Float =
  negate = select (x < 0.0) 1.0 0.0
  x = abs x
  ret1 = (-0.0187293 * x) + 0.0742610
  ret2 = (ret1 * x) - 0.2121144
  ret3 = (ret2 * x) + pi / 2.
  ret4 = (ret3 * (sqrt (1.0-x)))
  ret5 = ret4 - (2.0 * negate * ret4)
  negate * pi + ret5

  (x, y, z, w) = (q.x , q.y , q.z , q.w )
  v = [x, y, z]

  [x', y', z'] = normalize v
  a = acos (w / m)

    y' * a,
    z' * a,

Arguably one of the most important advantages of quaternions, "Slerp" stands for spherical linear interpolation. It's a function thats takes three parameters: a quaternion (q_{1}), a quaternion (q_{2}) and an interpolation parameter (t) that goes from (0) to (1).
